{
  "doc_id": "58824",
  "text": "In vivo, AP is expressed in the DP throughout the hair cycle [CITATION_1] , its level peaking during early anagen [CITATION_2] . In vitro, AP activity has been used as a marker for DP cells and AP levels decrease in culture as hairinducing activity declines [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . Nevertheless, our data show that in vitro expression of AP is not a reliable indicator of in vivo DP activity. Two other DP markers, CD133 (Prominin-1; Ito et al., 2007) and a8 integrin [CITATION_5] , are both expressed in all anagen follicles. Although spheres formed by CD133À cells were not only positive for AP but also for CD133 and a8 integrin, they did not induce follicles in skin reconstitution assays. It is therefore important to be cautious when interpreting the effects of different culture conditions on DP cells in the absence of in vivo data [CITATION_6] .",
